<subSubSection id="1FFC6501BD6EFFFFF892FB39EEE6FAE3" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5759368ABD6EFFFFF892FB39EEE6FAE3" blockId="1.[136,778,978,1766]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">
<emphasis id="6592EA98BD6EFFFFF892FB39ED72FB5E" bold="true" box="[189,294,1232,1258]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">Remark.</emphasis>
Note that 
<bibRefCitation id="33774B7BBD6EFFFFF99DFB38EEF2FB5E" author="Taeger, A. &amp; Blank, S. M. &amp; Liston, A. D." box="[434,678,1232,1259]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" pagination="1 - 1064" refId="ref5311" refString="Taeger, A., Blank, S. M. &amp; Liston, A. D. (2010) World catalog of Symphyta (Hymenoptera). Zootaxa, 2580 (1), 1 - 1064. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2580.1.1" type="journal article" year="2010">
Taeger 
<emphasis id="6592EA98BD6EFFFFFA22FB38EE11FB5E" box="[525,581,1232,1258]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">et al</emphasis>
. (2010)
</bibRefCitation>
ignored the 
<taxonomicName id="90E64D09BD6EFFFFF895FB1DED6FFABA" authorityName="Rasnitsyn" authorityYear="1977" box="[186,315,1268,1294]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Juralydinae">Juralydinae</taxonomicName>
in their list of the extant and fossil 
<taxonomicName id="90E64D09BD6EFFFFF8A7FAF1ED4BFA86" authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1890" box="[136,287,1304,1330]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pamphiliidae</taxonomicName>
, and considered its 
<typeStatus id="885D8828BD6EFFFFFA37FAF0EE1CFA87" box="[536,584,1305,1331]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">type</typeStatus>
genus 
<taxonomicName id="90E64D09BD6EFFFFFA89FAF1ED69FAE3" authority="Rasnitsyn, 1977" authorityName="Rasnitsyn" authorityYear="1977" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Juralyda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6592EA98BD6EFFFFFA89FAF1EF5EFA86" box="[678,778,1304,1330]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">Juralyda</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="33774B7BBD6EFFFFF8A7FAD4ED69FAE3" author="Rasnitsyn, A. P." box="[136,317,1341,1367]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" pagination="349 - 357" refId="ref4984" refString="Rasnitsyn, A. P. (1977) New Hymenoptera from the Jurassic and Cretaceous of Asia. Paleontological Journal, 11, 349 - 357." type="journal article" year="1977">Rasnitsyn, 1977</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
as a 
<taxonomicName id="90E64D09BD6EFFFFF95AFAD4EE5DFAE3" authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1890" box="[373,521,1341,1367]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pamphiliidae</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="6592EA98BD6EFFFFFA3FFAD7EEFFFAE3" box="[528,683,1341,1367]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">incertae sedis</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1FFC6501BD6EFFFFF892FA88EDB4F952" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="5759368ABD6EFFFFF892FA88EDB4F952" blockId="1.[136,778,978,1766]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">
<emphasis id="6592EA98BD6EFFFFF892FA88ED64FACF" bold="true" box="[189,304,1377,1403]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">Diagnosis</emphasis>
(modified after 
<bibRefCitation id="33774B7BBD6EFFFFFA22FA8BEEAAFACF" author="Wang, M. &amp; Shih, C. K. &amp; Ren, D. &amp; Rasnitsyn, A. P." box="[525,766,1377,1404]" pageId="1" pageNumber="174" pagination="391 - 397" refId="ref5434" refString="Wang, M., Shih, C. K., Ren, D. &amp; Rasnitsyn, A. P. (2014) A new fossil genus in Pamphiliidae (Hymenoptera) from China. Alcheringa, 38, 391 - 397. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 03115518.2014.884366" type="journal article" year="2014">
Wang 
<emphasis id="6592EA98BD6EFFFFFA4DFA8BEEF4FACF" box="[610,672,1377,1403]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="174">et al</emphasis>
., 2014
</bibRefCitation>
). First flagellomere distinctly thicker than following flagellomeres, twice to three times as long as second flagellomere. Forewing with Sc2 meeting R before 1- Rs (when preserved or present); 1-Rs always developed (Rs+M always separated from R) and about half as long as, or slightly longer than, half of 1-M; M+Cu gently bent, with ap-Cu extremely short when present; cell 1mcu shorter than length of pterostigma; cell 2r much wider than cell 2r-m, and 3r-m separated from 2m-cu by a distance equal or subequal to its length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
